 Farming-based Money flow 15 (1996) 113-126 
 
 Nonparametric analysis of technical, total/totally/with nothing else mixed in technical, and scale 
 (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) for food crop production in East Java, Indonesia 1 
 Richard V. Llewelyn *,Jeffery R. Williams 
 Department of Farming-based Money flow, Kansas State University, Manhattan, Kansas, USA 
 
 Accepted I August 1996 
 
 Abstract 
 Non parametric analysis of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) for watered farms in the Madiun regency in the west-central part of East Java, Indonesia 
 is conducted using linear programming ways of doing things. This procedure allows the relative technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) for each farm to be decided/figured out 
 and for inefficiencies to be rotten into total/totally/with nothing else mixed in technical inefficiency and scale inefficiency and does not require restrictions or 
 ideas (you think are true) (related to/looking at/thinking about) functional form to be placed on the data. 
 Farmers in Madiun generally are (producing a lot with very little waste) relative to each other. Farmers operating inefficiently do so more often because of scale 
 inefficiencies rather than total/totally/with nothing else mixed in technical inefficiencies. A rnajority of the farms operate in the area of decreasing returns to scale rather than 
 increasing returns to scale. Farmer age, the level of (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) of cropping activities, and high school education were found to be related 
 to technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) in the rainy season under watered conditions. Other (how money affects people's lives) factors were not (meaningful numbers). 
 The results suggest that inefficient farms use too much/too many levels of inputs, especially nitrogen (material that makes plants grow better). This is maybe due to the (staying around; not going away) 
 effects of past input subsidization policies, especially of (material that makes plants grow better)s, in Indonesia, or to risk-reducing behavior. The results also suggest that 
 current government policies to encourage (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) of cropping practices in Java may lead to greater technical inefficiencies in 
 production. Also, extension education targeted to younger farmers with low levels of formal education would improve (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
 
 Nonparametric analysis of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) for 
 watered farms in the Madiun regency of East Java, 
 Indonesia is conducted using linear programming 
 ways of doing things. Though common in high income countries, (wasting very little while working or producing something) analysis in poor 
 countries has been slowed by lack of data and 
 poor understanding of the production process and 
 often is limited to analysis of a single crop. Whole- 
 
