 farm analysis of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) that includes 
 multiproduct production is rare. The use of nonparametric ways of doing things makes it possible to test technical, total/totally/with nothing else mixed in technical, and scale (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) for multiproduct farms in Madiun and to then identify factors 
 connected with inefficiencies. 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) may be described as the relation between ends and means (Afriat) and has application in 
 production analysis as well as consumption explanation 
 and demand analysis. Money-flow experts widely distinguish 
 between technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) and allocative or price 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something), following discovering work by Farrell in 
 1957. The idea  of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) relates to 
 whether a firm uses the best available technology in 
 its production process (Chavas and Cox, 1988). In 
 
