 money-based terms, technical inefficiency refers to failure to operate on the production edge of something/unexplored area and generally is assumed to reflect inefficiencies caused by the 
 timing and method of use of production inputs (Byerlee, 1987). Potential causes of technical 
 inefficiency are not enough information or not enough (abilities to do particular job-related tasks well). 
 A variety of methods have been used to measure 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something). The idea  of the (producing a lot with very little waste) edge of something/unexplored area has 
 often been used, where mistakes from the edge of something/unexplored area 
 are assumed to represent inefficiencies. Different types 
 of edge of something/unexplored area (wasting very little while working or producing something) analysis exist. These methods 
 differ with respect to the ideas (you think are true) on the outer 
 bound of the edge of something/unexplored area, which may be pre-decided or 
 (random/including random data points), and to the method of measurement, parametric or non-parametric. 
 For the parametric approach, guess of production functions (or (money made/good thing received) or cost functions) consists of specifying a parametric form for the function 
 and then fitting it to watched/followed data by (making small) 
 some measure of their distance from the guessed 
 function. This method attributes difference/different version from the 
 (producing the most with the least waste) farms to technical inefficiency. As 
 Chavas and Aliber (1993) note, the parametric approach provides a consistent (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) for carefully studying (wasting very little while working or producing something), however, this approach has an important weakness, in that the maintained guess of 
 parametric form can never be detected directly 
 (Varian, 1984; Banker and Maindiratta, 1988). This 
 method this way forces restrictions on the technology 
 that may not hold and that affect the distribution and 
 measurement of the (wasting very little while working or producing something) terms (Chavas and 
 Aliber, 1993). An advantage of the parametric approach is that it can separate mistakes from the 
 edge of something/unexplored area technology into the planned or actual inefficiencies of the firm and the random parts/pieces, 
 such as weather, that are (random/including random data points) and not due to 
 operator inefficiency. Some (random/including random data points) creations 
 of edge of something/unexplored area production functions have been developed 
 that sort out the effects due to random errors from 
 those caused by technical inefficiencies. 
 An different approach is to apply nonparametric 
 ways of doing things to carefully study production (wasting very little while working or producing something). A pre-decided nonparametric edge of something/unexplored area model was developed 
 by Farrell (1957) in his new work. This 
 model cannot separate mistakes from the edge of something/unexplored area 
 technology into their planned and random parts/pieces and so, attributes all mistakes from the 
 
 edge of something/unexplored area technology to inefficiency of the watched/followed 
 firm and may overstate inefficiencies. However, this 
 way(s) of doing things has the advantage of (impressive/forcing (on people)/causing an inconvenient situation) no a 
 priori parametric restrictions on the hidden (under) technology, because it does not require a specific functional form for the edge of something/unexplored area to be specified. Therefore, it does not (force (on people)/cause an inconvenient situation) inappropriate structure on the 
 technology that might create a distortion in the (wasting very little while working or producing something) measures (Hire et al., 1985). Also, it can 
 handle disaggregated inputs and multiple output 
 technologies and can be used in testing technical, 
 allocative, scale and scope (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste). 
 This study uses nonparametric ways of doing things to 
 provide a direct analysis of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) of 
 watered food-crop production in East Java, Indonesia. A nonparametric, whole-farm, production edge of something/unexplored area that includes many outputs is guessed for 
 each farm in each of three clear/separate cropping seasons: 
 rainy, middle, and dry. The crops included in this study are paddy rice, com, soybeans, peanuts, mungbeans, cassava, and a pepper-onion intercrop. Relative overall technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) for each farm is 
 serious and stubborn as well as total/totally/with nothing else mixed in technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) and 
 scale (wasting very little while working or producing something). (wasting very little while working or producing something) indices received/got from the 
 nonparametric analysis are then moved backward on (how money affects people's lives) (numbers that change/things that change) to help identify factors connected 
 with technical inefficiencies. 
 
 1. Farming-based production and (wasting very little while working or producing something) in Indonesia and Asia 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) analysis of farming-based production in 
 Indonesia has focused mostly on watered rice 
 production (Widodo, 1986; Erwidodo, 1990) using 
 (random/including random data points) parametric approaches. Widodo used a 
 (random/including random data points) production function way(s) of doing things with 
 panel data to guess average technical (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste), 
 found to be between 83% and 96%. These values are 
 like those found by Dawson et al. (1991) in the 
 Philippines for lowland watered rice. In a almost the same 
 study, Erwidodo used two (random/including random data points) production 
 functions, the Cobb-Douglas and the translog, to 
 examine farm-level (wasting very little while working or producing something) in West Java. Technical (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) for (land with a layer of water) rice production averaged 
 93.5% and ranged from 88% to 96.4%. This way(s) of doing things showed/told about no a big difference in the level 
 of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) between small and large farms. 
 
 R.V. Llewelyn, J.R. Williams/ Farming-based Money flow 15 (1996) 113-126 
 
 Byerlee refers to six other studies that have taken 
 place in Asia, five of which examined watered rice 
 production and one that looked at com production, 
 all using (random/including random data points) production edge of something/unexplored area way(s) of doing things. 
 Average (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) for rice production ranged from 
 47% to 80% in India, the Philippines, and Pakistan. 
 For com, the average (wasting very little while working or producing something) in a study by Peng 
 and Chen in Taiwan (referred to by Byerlee, 1987) was 
 72%. The major factors explaining differences in 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) were (numbers that change/things that change) that dealt with farmers' 
 information and skills, such as education, experience, and contact with extension agents. 
 A study of watered, high-cooperating with/producing/giving up rice varieties in 
 India by Kalirajan (1981) used Cobb-Douglas technology in guessing a profit function to test the 
 relative (wasting very little while working or producing something) of large and small farmers who 
 had adopted modem varieties. He decided that 
 small farmers were as (producing a lot with very little waste) in putting into use the new 
 technologies as large farmers in terms of both technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) and allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
 In a study of rice production in the Philippines, 
 Berns ten ( 1977) included a measure of farmers' 
 technical knowledge in the production function. The 
 effect of this (number or thing that changes) was significant and positive. 
 He also found that age, experience, and extension 
 contact were significant factors in farmers' (wasting very little while working or producing something), but education was not significant. 
 Dawson et al. (1991) tested technical, allocative, and overall money-based (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) for 22 rice 
 farms in the Philippines with panel data from the 
 International Rice Research Institute using a edge of something/unexplored area 
 production function approach. Overall (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) 
 ranged from 84% to 95% across the farms. Azhar 
 ( 1991) found technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) in rice and wheat 
 production in Pakistan to be related positively and 
 very significantly to education levels, with first (or most important) 
 education providing the greatest increase in (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
 Little has been done concerning (wasting very little while working or producing something) of 
 secondary food-crop production in Indonesia. Also, the use of nonparametric ways of doing things to 
 Indonesian farming is almost (not existing at all), and 
 these ways of doing things have (possibility of/possible happening of)  providing 
 useful information (related to/looking at/thinking about) technical and scale (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) in production as well as factors connected 
 with inefficiencies that may exist. These ways of doing things 
 are useful where data are more limited and production technologies not well understood, since they do 
 
