 not require good  (detailed description of exactly what is required) of a functional 
 form. 
 
 2. Way(s) of doing things and model development 
 Although the use of parametric ways of doing things is 
 common, the use of nonparametric ways of doing things is 
 more limited, especially in poor countries, 
 even though nonparametric ways of doing things 
 can be used as it wasations where data is more limited 
 and where production technologies are less well 
 understood. There are two nonparametric approaches 
 to production analysis. One is based on the works of 
 Afriat, 1972; Hanoch and Rothschild, 1972; and 
 Varian, 1984. This approach deals with four types of 
 concerns in the neoclassical explanation of production: 
 consistency, restriction of form, recoverability, and 
 prediction, without maintaining any guesses of 
 functional form. This way(s) of doing things is applied to time 
 series data and has been used in a few studies to 
 test technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) in farming (e.g. 
 Chavas and Aliber, 1993; Chavas and Cox, 1988). 
 Or, Farrell rotten (wasting very little while working or producing something) into 
 technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) and allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something). Hire et 
 al. ( 1985) introduced a nonparametric method of 
 calculating (wasting very little while working or producing something) across farms, which extended 
 Farrell's approach by relaxing the (serving to severely limit or control) ideas (you think are true) of constant returns to scale and of strong 
 disposability of inputs, the major criticisms of the 
 method. 
 Fare et al. note that (wasting very little while working or producing something) by a firm in inputs 
 does not suggest that the firm is necessarily (producing a lot with very little waste) 
 in outputs. Technical, allocative, and other (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 measures of outputs cannot be known from corresponding (wasting very little while working or producing something) measures of inputs or crime 
 versa because output and input (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) focus on 
 different parts of production. The type of (wasting very little while working or producing something) that is being tested should be clearly 
 specified. 
 Technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) may be defined as the ability 
 of a firm to produce as much output as possible with 
 a specified level of inputs, given the existing technology. Graphically, this is illustrated in Fig. I. Six 
 watched/followed data points with connected levels of input 
 and output are shown. The edge of something/unexplored area for this production process is defined by the line ABC. (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) A, B, and C lie on the edge of something/unexplored area while observa- 
 
