 the origin is unrelated topic to the edge of something/unexplored area at Point B. This 
 ray represents constant returns to scale for the technology represented by these data (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements). In 
 this example, (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) B is overall (compared to other things) 
 technically (producing a lot with very little waste), which hints that this firm is 
 also purely technically (producing a lot with very little waste) and scale (producing a lot with very little waste). It 
 lies on the edge of something/unexplored area and has constant returns to scale. 
 Although a firm may be technically inefficient in 
 an overall sense, it is possible for it to be purely 
 technically (producing a lot with very little waste), while experiencing inefficiencies in scale. This is also illustrated in Fig. 1. 
 (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements) A and C are purely technically (producing a lot with very little waste), since they lie on the edge of something/unexplored area, but show scale 
 inefficiencies. (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) D is both scale inefficient 
 and purely technically inefficient since it lies below 
 the edge of something/unexplored area. Possibly, the same level of input 
 could be used to (accomplish or gain with effort) a higher level of output, 
 which would allow this producer to be on the edge of something/unexplored area between Points B and C. (instance of watching, noticing, or making a statement) E is purely 
 technically inefficient since it is not on the production edge of something/unexplored area, but is scale (producing a lot with very little waste), because it produces at input level x2, the scale-(producing a lot with very little waste) level of 
 input. 
 The model used in this study is based on a 
 model developed by Grabowski and Pasurka ( 1987) 
 to examine relative (wasting very little while working or producing something) of farms in the north- 
 
 em and southern United States before the Civil 
 War. Using this way(s) of doing things, overall technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) for a farm is serious and stubborn and then is rotten into total/totally/with nothing else mixed in technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) and scale (wasting very little while working or producing something) for multiproduct, farm-level, crop production 
 in Madiun, Indonesia. With this approach, a nonparametric production edge of something/unexplored area is built, with 
 inefficiency being measured by the extent to which 
 firms operate below the edge of something/unexplored area. Using this approach, the cause of the inefficiency can be set apart and given out 
 as either inappropriate scale (scale inefficiency) or 
 off-isoquant production (pure technical inefficiency). 
 It should be noted that this procedure involves 
 relative technical (wasting very little while working or producing something), that is, the production 
 edge of something/unexplored area is built from the data and each farm's 
 performance is compared with the edge of something/unexplored area to point to/show 
 overall technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) of the individual farm. 
 Risk is not included clearly in the model. The 
 model assumes that the degree of risk disgust is 
 the same across all farms in the sample, but does 
 not assume the degree of risk disgust, that is, 
 whether this group of farmers are risk-taking, riskneutral, or risk disliking. If this idea (you think is true) of constant 
 risk preference does not hold, the guessed inefficiencies will be overstated. Some say that 
 risk preferences may be different especially between large and small farms. However, the regres- 
 
 R.V. Llewelyn, J.R. Williams/ Farming-based Money flow 15 (1996) 113-126 
 
 sion analysis conducted to test factors connected with inefficiency includes farm size as a possible factor, but as shown later, this is not (related to numbers) 
 related to inefficiency. 
 This analysis also assumes (group of things that are all pretty much the same) inputs. 
 Land is not included clearly in the model and it is 
 assumed that differences/different versions in soil types and life-creating ability do 
 not exist. This is a rather strong idea (you think is true), but 
 necessary in order to go ahead. Though data for difference/different version in land quality were not collected, the data for 
 each of the four villages surveyed were tested separately to test whether there might be large differences in land quality. These results are reported 
 below, but no a big differences in technical 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) are found to exist between villages. Evenness of other inputs, including labor, chemicals, seed, and management, is assumed also. 
 Differences in labor and management quality would 
 be very hard to decide/figure out and include in the 
 model. 
