 returns to scale. A firm operating at increasing returns to scale should increase input use in order to 
 (accomplish or gain with effort) (making a lot of an item so each item costs less). This would mean moving from Point A to Point B in Fig. 1 to increase 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something). A situation in which farms are operating 
 at decreasing returns to scale hints that small 
 farms are doable/possible and that large farms would be better 
 off to decrease input levels or at least not increase 
 them, because to do so would be to further increase 
 inefficiency connected with returns to scale. 
 Money-based (wasting very little while working or producing something) tests only test actual 
 working well relative to possible working well and do 
 not suggest weird thinking on the part of farmers who are 
 inefficient. The failure of farmers to use the most 
 (producing a lot with very little waste) ways of doing things of production may be due to the 
 cost of the purchase/getting/learning of information for an individual farmer being greater than the benefits or maybe 
 due to fixed valuable things, property rights, and (living somewhere), as 
 well as non-money-based goals of the farmers 
 (Byerlee, 1987). 
 To help identify possible factors related to inefficiencies, the (wasting very little while working or producing something) indices decided/figured out from the 
 linear programming problems are moved backward on ex- 
 
 R. V. Llewelyn, J.R. Williams/ Farming-based Money flow 15 0996) 113-126 
 
 planatory (numbers that change/things that change) of age, education, farm size, and 
 (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) using a Tobit analysis to (ask lots of questions about/try to find the truth about) the effect 
 of these (numbers that change/things that change) on the technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) of the 
 individual farms. 
 This analysis can be helpful in targeting extension 
 activities to deal with technical inefficiencies in production. The linear Tobit moving backward in Eq. (II) is 
 used to identify possible factors connected with inefficiency. Tobit analysis is used because the (things that change (like test scores) because of other things that you control (like study times)), overall technical (wasting very little while working or producing something), pure 
 technical (wasting very little while working or producing something), and scale (wasting very little while working or producing something), are changed (numbers that change/things that change), having an upper limit of I.OO. Each 
 of these indices is moved backward on the explanatory 
 (numbers that change/things that change) of age, education, farm size, percent of 
 land owned, and (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing). Dummy (numbers that change/things that change) 
 are used for education, representing junior high 
 school and high school. The limits/guidelines, B3 and 8 4 , 
 provide an idea of how much added/more levels of 
 education after the first (or most important) level affect (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
 The changeable percent of land owned is an attempt to 
 test the effects of land (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) on technical (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
