 4. Analysis and results 
 
 Using the linear programming way(s) of doing things organized and listed earlier, nonparametric analysis of relative technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) is performed for food crop production on watered farms in each of the three seasons. 
 Three linear programs (Eq. (3), Eq. (6), and Eq. 
 (10)) are solved to provide the values of 0, A, and 'Y 
 for each individual farm. Table 2 summarizes the 
 crops tested in each seasonal analysis and the 
 
 R. V. Llewelyn, J.R. Williams/ Farming-based Money flow 15 (1996) 113-126 
 
 number of farms in the sample which produce each 
 crop. A total of 61 farms is tested for technical 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) in this analysis. 
 Average, lowest value, and highest overall technical (wasting very little while working or producing something), total/totally/with nothing else mixed in technical (wasting very little while working or producing something), and scale 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) are reported for each season in Table 3, as 
 well as the number of farms operating at constant, 
 increasing, and decreasing returns to scale. The average overall (wasting very little while working or producing something) is calculated by dividing 1I 8 
 for each farm to get the overall (wasting very little while working or producing something) level 
 for that farm. This level of (wasting very little while working or producing something) then is averaged over all the farms in the sample. A farm that is 
 technically (producing a lot with very little waste) has an (wasting very little while working or producing something) of 100%. Average total/totally/with nothing else mixed in technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) is calculated by dividing 1/ A for each farm and averaging these values, 
 and average scale (wasting very little while working or producing something) is figured out by/decided by dividing A/ (J for each farm and averaging these values 
 for the whole sample. Scale (producing a lot with very little waste) farms operate at 
 constant returns to scale in inputs (input level x2 on 
 Fig. 1), whereas those with decreasing returns have 
 input levels that are too high and those with increasing returns to scale have input levels that are too 
 low. Scale-inefficient firms may be purely technically (producing a lot with very little waste) (operating on the edge of something/unexplored area) but are not 
 using the correct level of input. 
 
