 Results of the (wasting very little while working or producing something) analysis in the rainy 
 season are summarized in Table 3. Overall and pure 
 technical (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) are high, as are scale (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste). The average overall technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) of 
 98.1% is (a) little higher than but almost the same as 
 values in other studies in Indonesia and Asia that 
 used a parametric approach in testing rice production (Widodo, 1986; Erwidodo, 1990; Dawson et 
 al., 1991). This study had a much larger sample size 
 than Dawson et al., and (a) little larger than the other 
 two studies. In a small sample, a few inefficient 
 farms would influence the results more than in a 
 larger sample. 
 The range in overall technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) is between 84.4% and 100%, with 44 of the 61 farms 
 (72.1 %) being overall technically (producing a lot with very little waste), that is 
 8 = 1. An added six farms are purely technically 
 (producing a lot with very little waste), meaning they operate on the production 
 edge of something/unexplored area but not at constant returns to scale. The 
 average total/totally/with nothing else mixed in technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) is 98.8%, with a 
 minimum of 87.6%, pointing to/showing that the most purely 
 technically inefficient farm could only increase output by about 12.4% through (producing more with less waste) use of 
 inputs. Average scale (wasting very little while working or producing something) is 99.2% with a 
 minimum of 90.4%. Little difference/different version in these measures is obvious, with the standard mistakes ranging 
 from 0.019 to 0.043. Constant returns to scale are 
 obvious for 45 of the farms. Increasing returns to 
 scale hold for only one farm and 15 farms experience decreasing returns to scale. 
 In the middle season, average overall (wasting very little while working or producing something) is 
 95.5% with the highest (wasting very little while working or producing something) of 64.6%, as 
 shown in Table 3. Forty-one farms are technically 
 (producing a lot with very little waste), with seven of the remaining farms being 
 purely technically (producing a lot with very little waste). Forty-three farms have 
 constant returns to scale, whereas eight have increasing returns to scale and ten have decreasing returns. 
 The lower (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) connected with the middle 
 season for these farms may be explained by a situation where rainfall may change/differ  across farms leading to 
 production responses which would not be captured 
 by the (wasting very little while working or producing something) analysis. The low rainfall in the dry 
 season is consistent for all parts of the regency, 
 while in the rainy season, rainfall is more consistent 
 across all farms than in the middle season. Rainfall 
 data by village are not available for analysis. 
 Relative technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) in the dry season is 
 summarized in Table 3. Average (wasting very little while working or producing something) is 97.7%, 
 
 with the highest (wasting very little while working or producing something) at 73.8%. Fifty of the 
 farms are overall technically (producing a lot with very little waste), with all but 
 three farms being purely technically (producing a lot with very little waste). Average total/totally/with nothing else mixed in technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) is 98.9%, and average 
 scale (wasting very little while working or producing something) is 98.7%. The 50 overall technically 
 (producing a lot with very little waste) farms operate at constant returns to scale, 
 whereas 10 of the 11 remaining farms have decreasing returns to scale, and one farm shows increasing 
 returns to scale. 
 Higher (material that makes plants grow better) use, especially of urea, seems 
 to be connected with the least (producing a lot with very little waste) farms in each 
 season, with average urea use of farms found to be 
 overall technically inefficient higher than the average 
 for the whole sample, with the least (producing a lot with very little waste) farm in 
 each season having the highest use of urea. High 
 (material that makes plants grow better) use may reflect a risk sneaky action, though 
 some studies have found that producers with higher 
 levels of risk disgust would be less likely to prefer 
 high levels of nitrogen (the adding of things to soil to make plants grow better) (Williams et al., 
 1992; SriRamaratnam et al., 1987). 
 Because of the idea (you think is true) of evenness of 
 inputs, especially of land quality, the (wasting very little while working or producing something) 
 analysis was conducted for each of the four villages 
 where data were collected. If (group of things that are all pretty much the same) land 
 quality is wrongly assumed and land differences 
 actually account for the measured inefficiencies found 
 in the above analysis, the average (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) for 
 each village should be 100% or nearly so, since the 
 edge of something/unexplored area for each individual village would be less 
 than or equal to the group production edge of something/unexplored area for 
 all farms. 
 However, in each season, the average (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) 
 for each individual village are only (a) little higher 
 than the averages for the group sample and none 
 are equal to 100%. In the rainy season, the average 
 overall technical (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) for the four villages are 
 98.2%, 98.8%, 98.7%, and 98.4%, (match up each pair of items in order), 
 compared with the average for the whole sample of 
 98.1 %. The overall technical (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) by village 
 in the middle season average 95.7%, 96.1 %, 96.1 %, 
 and 95.8%, (match up each pair of items in order), while the average overall 
 technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) for the dry season for each village is equal to 97.9%, 97.8%, 98.2%, and 98.4%. 
 The average overall (wasting very little while working or producing something) for the whole sample 
 is equal to 95.5% for the middle season and 97.7% 
 for the dry season. The results are almost the same  for pure 
 technical and scale (measures of output versus waste/getting more with less waste) for each village as 
 well. This points to/shows that assuming (group of things that are all pretty much the same) land 
 
