 6. Summary and ends/end results 
 Nonparametric analysis of technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) for 
 watered farms in Madiun, Indonesia is conducted 
 using models based on ways of doing things developed and 
 used by Grabowski and Pasurka (1987). This procedure allows the relative technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) for each 
 farm to be decided/figured out and for inefficiencies to be 
 rotten into total/totally/with nothing else mixed in technical inefficiency (operating off of the isoquant or production edge of something/unexplored area) and 
 scale inefficiency (not producing at constant returns 
 to scale in input use). This way(s) of doing things also allows 
 for multi-input, multi-output situations and does not 
 require restrictions or ideas (you think are true) (related to/looking at/thinking about) functional form to be placed on the data. This analysis 
 provides information on the technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) of 
 multiproduct food-crop producing farms in Indonesia 
 and some of the factors connected with inefficiency. 
 Testing farms for each season under watered 
 conditions shows that average overall technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) is 98.1% in the rainy season, while in the 
 middle season it is 95.5% and is (a) little higher at 
 97.7% in the dry season. In each case, the majority 
 of farms are technically and scale (producing a lot with very little waste), operating 
 at constant returns to scale. Most farms that are scale 
 inefficient are operating at decreasing returns to scale, 
 pointing to/showing too much/too many input levels. 
 Tobit analysis to test inefficiency shows that 
 farmers' age and the level of (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) are the 
 most (meaningful numbers) factors connected with 
 technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) measures. A quadratic relationship between age and (wasting very little while working or producing something) exists in each season, with (wasting very little while working or producing something) increasing with age at first, 
 then decreasing. Greater (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) is connected 
 with lower (wasting very little while working or producing something) levels in the rainy and dry 
 seasons for each of the three (wasting very little while working or producing something) indices. The 
 
 125 
 
 same relationship happens in the middle season only 
 for scale (wasting very little while working or producing something). 
 Also, having a high school education is 
 related positively to higher levels of total/totally/with nothing else mixed in technical 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) in the rainy and middle seasons and with 
 scale (wasting very little while working or producing something) in the rainy and dry seasons but at a 
 lower confidence level than age or (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) 
 (a= 0.1 0). None of the other (numbers that change/things that change), including 
 farm size, (length of time at work or in power/right to permanent employment) arrangements, or junior high school 
 education is (meaningful numbers) in any season. 
 Farmers operating inefficiently are doing so more 
 often because of scale inefficiencies rather than pure 
 technical inefficiencies, and most of these 
 farmers are operating at decreasing returns to scale 
 in inputs rather than increasing returns to scale, often 
 using higher levels of (material that makes plants grow better), especially nitrogen, 
 than (producing more with less waste) farmers. In Indonesia, (compared to other things) 
 high (material that makes plants grow better) payments have been in place until the 
 early 1990s and since have (lowered in number/got worse/gotten worse) by over 20%. 
 The data in this study were collected in 1994, after 
 the reduction in the (material that makes plants grow better) helping payment began. Some 
 farmers may still be using higher levels of (material that makes plants grow better) 
 than are (producing a lot with very little waste), maybe due to continuing production ways of doing things which began when (material that makes plants grow better)s were 
 paid-for. This may account for the decreasing 
 returns to scale found to exist. Another possibility is 
 that this is a risk-reducing plan, Williams et al. 
 ( 1992) and SriRamaratnam et al. ( 1987) have shown 
 this may not be true. It should be noted that the 
 majority of farms in this sample operate at constant 
 returns to scale, pointing to/showing that they are using correct 
 levels of inputs, relative to other farms in the sample. 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) increases, then eventually (lowers in number/gets worse) with 
 age. This is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with what would be expected. 
 Targeting younger and older farmers for extension 
 activities could increase their levels of technical 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something) relative to middle (old/allowed to get old/got older) farmers. 
 Higher levels of (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) in cropping practices are related to lower technical (wasting very little while working or producing something), 
 especially in the rainy and dry seasons. Farmers 
 who are more (made to do one thing very well) with only one or two crops 
 grown in a season have higher levels of technical 
 (wasting very little while working or producing something). So, government programs that have 
 tried to (change to flow on a different path/change to point to, or focus on, something else) cropland away from rice production toward secondary food crop production may 
 actually lead to increased technical inefficiency in 
 production. 
 Having a high school education is related to 
 
 126 
 
 R. V. Llewelyn, J.R. Williams/ Farming-based Money flow 15 U996) 113-126 
 
 higher technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) in production in this study. 
 Only 7% of the sample of farmers have a high 
 school education, but these farmers (based on what's seen or what seems obvious) are 
 able to operate at much higher technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) than other farmers. These results suggest that 
 extension education could be effective, especially if 
 targeted to farmers who have had limited educational 
 opportunities. Those with college levels 
 may have access to information that farmers with 
 only elementary or junior high school education do 
 not. Providing access to information to farmers with 
 lower levels of education may help them to increase 
 technical (wasting very little while working or producing something) in production relative to farmers 
 with higher levels of education. 
 
